# Pear Diamond Bracelet: Complete Buyer's Guide {{year}}

## TL;DR: Pear Cut Diamond Bracelet — What to Know Before Shopping

- Pear diamonds in bracelets are **always set east-west** (horizontally). The shape's point-to-belly length makes vertical setting physically impractical at bracelet scale. Every pear diamond tennis bracelet you find places the stones lying sideways across the band.
- The single most important decision: **accent bracelet** (pear diamonds alternating with rounds, lower entry price, familiar look) vs. **feature bracelet** (all-pear east-west continuous line or station design, maximum pear diamond presence, higher CTW commitment). These are different products that serve different purposes.
- **Best entry-level pear diamond bracelet:** [Diamond Tennis Bracelet with Pear Diamond Accent in 14K White Gold (3 CTW)](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/bracelets/diamond-tennis-bracelet-with-pear-diamond-accent-in-14k-white-gold-3-ct-tw-item-753000?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) at ~~$7,895~~ **$7,105** (-10%). → The Extraordinary Collection design alternates large pear diamonds with round brilliant accents — the closest product to the "featured pear stone" aesthetic most buyers expect.
- **Best all-pear bracelet:** [Dainty East-West Pear Cut Diamond Tennis Bracelet in 14K White Gold (5¼ CTW)](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/bracelets/dainty-east-west-pear-cut-diamond-tennis-bracelet-in-14k-white-gold-5-1-4-ct-tw-item-752577?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) at **$16,285**. → Every single stone is a pear diamond set horizontally for maximum width and directional fire.
- **Best lab grown value:** [Pear Lab Grown Diamond Bangle in 14K White Gold (8 CTW)](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/bracelets/pear-lab-grown-diamond-bangle-bracelet-in-14k-white-gold-8-ct-tw-item-753884?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) at **$12,145** — also available in yellow gold at the same price. → 8 carats of lab pear diamonds for less than the all-natural entry-level tennis bracelet.
- Priority: understand CTW before comparing prices. In an accent bracelet, the "3 CTW" covers both pear and round stones combined — the pear portion is 40–60% of that total. In an all-pear tennis bracelet, every carat is a pear stone. The same number is a completely different product.

## What Makes a Pear Diamond Bracelet Different From Every Other Bracelet

A pear cut diamond bracelet is one of the most widely misunderstood jewelry purchases online. Most buyers type "pear diamond bracelet" while picturing something with a single large pear stone dramatically centered — like a pendant-style design that wraps the wrist. What Blue Nile's catalog actually contains is fundamentally different: multi-stone formats where pear diamonds appear either as every stone in a continuous horizontal line or as alternating accent elements within a longer diamond design.

This is not a catalog limitation. It reflects the physical reality of working with pear diamonds at bracelet scale. The pear shape's asymmetric proportions, its pointed tip, and its variable length-to-width ratios all create setting requirements that determine how these stones can and cannot appear on the wrist. Understanding those requirements before looking at a single price is what separates a confident purchase from buyer's remorse.

This guide covers all six Blue Nile pear diamond bracelet designs currently available: what they are, what CTW actually means across each format, and exactly which one fits your situation.

[![Blue Nile pear diamond bracelets — station, tennis, bangle and accent styles](  /images/bn-pear-bracelet-1.avif)](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry?ComponentIDs=Bracelet&Diamonds=Dia,Lab&stoneShape=pear&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)

## The Silhouette Trap

The mental image most buyers carry into a pear diamond bracelet search is specific: a single, dramatic pear-cut stone featured prominently against a delicate chain or band — something with the presence of a pear diamond pendant worn on the wrist. This image does not match any product in Blue Nile's bracelet lineup.

The closest product is the [Diamond Tennis Bracelet with Pear Diamond Accent](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/bracelets/diamond-tennis-bracelet-with-pear-diamond-accent-in-14k-white-gold-3-ct-tw-item-753000?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational), which alternates large pear stones with round brilliants in a repeating pattern. It prominently features pear diamonds. It is still a continuous bracelet format where the pear stones share real estate with rounds — not a single featured stone with a simple chain.

The Silhouette Trap causes two distinct purchase errors. First, buyers reject the entire pear diamond bracelet category because "none of these are what I had in mind," without recognizing that east-west tennis bracelets and accent designs are actually the most technically sophisticated way to work pear diamonds at the wrist. The shape demands east-west orientation at this scale, and the designs in the catalog are specifically engineered to make that orientation look intentional rather than forced. Second, buyers who do proceed often compare CTW numbers across incompatible formats — a 3 CTW accent bracelet where pears represent only half the weight, versus a 5 CTW all-pear tennis where every carat is a pear stone. The numbers look close. The products are not.

Understanding what the category actually contains — before evaluating a single product — is the first requirement for a good purchase.

