## The East-West Mandate

Every pear diamond set in a bracelet must be oriented east-west — horizontally across the wrist, with the point and belly of the pear perpendicular to the direction the bracelet runs. This is not a stylistic choice made by designers. It is a geometric requirement imposed by the pear shape itself.

A pear diamond's length-to-width ratio typically runs between 1.45:1 and 1.75:1. At the stone sizes used in bracelets — typically 0.08 to 0.35 carats per stone — this length creates a structural problem in vertical orientation. The individual bracelet link would need to span the full length of the stone perpendicular to the bracelet's direction of movement. The resulting link would be too tall off the wrist, too mechanically rigid to flex through the bracelet's range of motion, and visually disproportionate compared to the bracelet's width.

East-west orientation solves all three problems simultaneously. The pear's width — the shorter dimension — now runs parallel to the bracelet's length, creating compact links that flex correctly and lie flat against the wrist. The point and belly become the top and bottom edges of each link. A continuous line of east-west pear diamonds produces a distinctive fan-like visual pattern, where each stone's asymmetric geometry catches light at a different angle across the wrist's curved surface.

This directional sparkle is the fundamental difference between a pear diamond tennis bracelet and a round diamond tennis bracelet at equivalent CTW. Round stones produce uniform omnidirectional fire — every stone looks the same from any angle. East-west pear stones produce angled, directional fire that shifts dynamically as the wrist moves. The fire pattern is not uniform — it changes with the angle of observation, creating a bracelet that looks noticeably different in movement than it does at rest.

