## The CTW Divide

Total carat weight is the most deceptive number on a bracelet product page. Across the four pear diamond bracelet formats at Blue Nile — accent tennis, east-west tennis, station, and bangle — the same CTW figure means something completely different.

In an **accent tennis bracelet** such as the [3 CTW Pear Accent at $7,105](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/bracelets/diamond-tennis-bracelet-with-pear-diamond-accent-in-14k-white-gold-3-ct-tw-item-753000?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational), the CTW covers every diamond in the bracelet — pear stones and round accents combined. The pear stones are the more prominent elements, but they likely represent 40–60% of the total weight. A 3 CTW accent bracelet contains approximately 1.2–1.8 CTW of actual pear diamond material.

In an **all-pear east-west tennis bracelet** such as the [5¼ CTW Dainty at $16,285](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/bracelets/dainty-east-west-pear-cut-diamond-tennis-bracelet-in-14k-white-gold-5-1-4-ct-tw-item-752577?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational), every carat in the CTW is a pear diamond. No dilution, no shared weight with rounds, no split. 5.25 CTW means 5.25 carats of pear diamond.

In a **station bracelet** such as the [Fancy Shape Station at $28,245–$37,925](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/bracelets/fancy-shape-diamond-station-bracelet-in-14k-yellow-gold-7-ct-tw-item-753599?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational), the CTW covers only the individual station diamonds — the groups of featured stones at set intervals along the bracelet. The connecting chain or metalwork between stations is not counted. This means the CTW is concentrated at the featured positions, making each individual station cluster substantially heavier and more visible than equivalent-CTW tennis stones.

In a **bangle bracelet** such as the [Pear Lab Grown Bangle at $12,145](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/bracelets/pear-lab-grown-diamond-bangle-bracelet-in-14k-white-gold-8-ct-tw-item-753884?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational), the CTW covers all stones distributed around the rigid band. Depending on whether the bangle is fully paved or partially set, the weight represents either total surface coverage or a partial arrangement.

Comparing CTW across these four formats gives you meaningless numbers. A buyer who sees "8 CTW lab bangle at $12,145" and "5¼ CTW natural tennis at $16,285" and concludes the bangle is the better value by CTW is comparing apples to a door handle. Lab vs. natural aside, the formats deliver entirely different visual experiences. Make your format decision first, then compare CTW within that format.

