The [Pear Lab Grown Diamond Bangle](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/bracelets/pear-lab-grown-diamond-bangle-bracelet-in-14k-white-gold-8-ct-tw-item-753884?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the format outlier in this category and the highest CTW-per-dollar piece in the lineup. At 8 carats of lab grown pear diamonds available in both white and yellow gold at an identical $12,145, it delivers more stone weight than the all-natural Dainty East-West Tennis (5¼ CTW at $16,285) for $4,140 less.

The bangle format fundamentally changes the wearing experience compared to a flexible tennis bracelet. A rigid bracelet does not flex or shift on the wrist — it passes over the hand and sits in a fixed position. This makes it easier to stack with other bangles and eliminates the minor movement that tennis bracelets experience during activity. The trade-off is fit: a bangle cannot be resized the way a tennis bracelet can by adding or removing links. Sizing is based on the hand's widest point when fingers are pressed together, not the wrist circumference.

Lab grown pear diamonds in this bangle are chemically identical to natural pear diamonds — same hardness (10 Mohs), same refractive index (2.417), same fire and scintillation properties. The difference is origin, not material properties. At bracelet stone sizes (likely 0.15–0.35ct per stone in the bangle), a gemologist looking through a loupe would see no visual difference between lab and natural. In this format, the lab grown argument is purely economic: do you want 8 CTW of pear diamonds or 5.25 CTW of pear diamonds for a similar budget?

