## Metal Guide: White Gold vs. Yellow Gold for Pear Diamond Bracelets

Pear diamond bracelets at Blue Nile are available exclusively in 14K white gold and 14K yellow gold. There is no platinum option in the current pear bracelet lineup, and no rose gold option.

**14K White Gold** is the default for most pear diamond bracelet buyers. The cool neutral tone maximizes contrast with the pear diamond's colorless fire — the stones appear brighter against a silver-white metal background than they would against warm yellow. White gold is also the most versatile stacking choice; it pairs with yellow gold accents without competing and blends into a mixed-metal wrist stack without overpowering it.

**14K Yellow Gold** changes the visual character of pear diamonds in a meaningful way. Against a warm yellow background, even colorless pear stones take on a subtly warm tone — this is not a color grade issue but a perceptual effect from the metal surrounding the stone. Yellow gold pear diamond bracelets read warmer, more vintage, and more romantic in overall character. If your engagement ring, most-worn watch, or existing fine jewelry collection is yellow gold, the yellow gold bracelet is the correct match regardless of personal preference.

<table class="dc-custom-table"><thead><tr><th>Metal</th><th>Products Available</th><th>Price Range</th><th>Best For</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>14K White Gold</strong></td><td>Pear Accent Tennis, Fancy Cluster, Dainty E/W Tennis, Lab Bangle, Station Fashion</td><td>$7,105–$37,925</td><td>Maximum diamond contrast; versatile stacking; modern aesthetic</td></tr><tr><td><strong>14K Yellow Gold</strong></td><td>Fancy Shape Station, Lab Grown Bangle</td><td>$12,145–$28,245</td><td>Warm vintage look; matching yellow gold collections</td></tr></tbody></table>

Metal matching rule for bracelets mirrors the rule for rings: your bracelet metal should match the metal family of your most-worn fine jewelry. Mixing 14K yellow gold with 14K white gold reads as intentional contrast only when other pieces in the stack deliberately bridge the two tones. When in doubt, match your engagement ring or your watch case.

## Lab Grown vs. Natural Pear Diamonds in Bracelets

The pear diamond bracelet category at Blue Nile currently contains one lab grown option (the Pear Lab Grown Bangle) and five natural diamond designs. The pricing difference between lab and natural at equivalent CTW is significant enough to warrant a direct comparison before making a purchase decision.

The [all-natural Dainty East-West Pear Tennis at $16,285](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/bracelets/dainty-east-west-pear-cut-diamond-tennis-bracelet-in-14k-white-gold-5-1-4-ct-tw-item-752577?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) delivers 5¼ CTW of natural pear diamonds in a flexible tennis format. The [Pear Lab Grown Bangle at $12,145](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/bracelets/pear-lab-grown-diamond-bangle-bracelet-in-14k-white-gold-8-ct-tw-item-753884?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) delivers 8 CTW of lab pear diamonds in a rigid bangle format — 2.75 more carats, $4,140 less. These are not directly comparable because the formats are different, but the CTW-per-dollar gap is substantial.

The resale argument favors natural diamonds. Natural pear diamonds maintain market value over decades; lab grown diamonds have experienced consistent price compression as production scales up. For a bracelet intended as a long-term investment or family heirloom, the natural stone's value retention matters. For a bracelet intended for personal enjoyment without a resale consideration, the lab grown argument is straightforward: more diamond per dollar, identical visual properties.

There is one practical argument for natural diamonds in bracelets that has nothing to do with resale: the flexibility to sell individual stones later if the bracelet is ever disassembled or repurposed. Natural pear diamonds of the quality found in fine jewelry bracelets retain individual resale value at wholesale. Lab grown stones at resale are worth a fraction of the original purchase price regardless of quality grade.

## Size and Fit: What Blue Nile's Product Pages Don't Explain

Tennis bracelets at Blue Nile come in 7-inch and 8-inch lengths. The 7-inch length fits most adult wrists (6.5–7.5 inch wrist circumference) with approximately half an inch of comfortable drape. The 8-inch length is for larger wrists or buyers who prefer a looser, more relaxed fit. Neither length can be custom-ordered between these two options, and unlike rings, the fit cannot be adjusted at a local jeweler by adding or removing stones — the only practical adjustment is swapping the clasp for a longer or shorter version.

Measure your wrist with a flexible tape measure and add 0.5 inches for a standard bracelet fit. Add 1 inch if you prefer your bracelets to drape visibly rather than sit snug. Choose 7-inch for the standard result, 8-inch only if the measurement exceeds 7.5 inches.

For the bangle, fit works on completely different logic. A bangle passes over the hand to rest on the wrist — the inner diameter must accommodate your hand at its widest point when all four fingers are pressed together, not your wrist circumference. Most adults with average hand proportions need an inner diameter between 2.25 and 2.5 inches. Measure your hand's widest circumference with fingers together, divide by 3.14 to get the required inner diameter, and add 0.1 inches for passage comfort. Blue Nile provides the inner diameter in the product details tab — do not order a bangle based on wrist measurement alone.

## Stacking Pear Diamond Bracelets With Other Pieces

Pear diamond bracelets stack differently from round diamond tennis bracelets because the east-west orientation's visual width creates a slightly broader profile. A single east-west pear tennis bracelet appears wider on the wrist than a round tennis bracelet of equivalent CTW because the pear stones' widths are oriented along the bracelet's face rather than perpendicular to it.

The most successful stacks pair an east-west pear tennis bracelet with a thinner plain metal band on one side and a single delicate chain bracelet on the other. This gives the pear bracelet visual breathing room rather than crowding it with competing diamond rows. When a pear tennis bracelet is pressed up against another diamond tennis bracelet, the two sets of east-west stones can create a visually busy overlap — the pear bracelet performs better with contrast pieces than with matching elements.

The [Pear Lab Grown Bangle](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/bracelets/pear-lab-grown-diamond-bangle-bracelet-in-14k-white-gold-8-ct-tw-item-753884?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the ideal foundation piece for a wrist stack. Its rigid format provides a stable anchor that does not shift, and its all-over pear diamond coverage means it reads as both an accent piece and a statement depending on what flanks it. A bangle plus a thin yellow gold chain plus a watch is a complete and balanced wrist composition at any budget level.

The [Pear Diamond Accent Tennis](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/bracelets/diamond-tennis-bracelet-with-pear-diamond-accent-in-14k-white-gold-3-ct-tw-item-753000?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the easiest piece to stack because the alternating pear-and-round format already incorporates visual variety. It combines with plain bands, colored stone bracelets, and watch straps without conflict.

