## Expert Summary

> The pear diamond bracelet category rewards buyers who make one decision clearly before looking at prices: accent or feature. An accent bracelet gives you pear diamond presence in a design that blends the pear shape with the familiar round brilliant — it is the entry point, the most wearable choice, and the safest gift. A feature bracelet, whether the all-pear east-west tennis or the mixed-shape station designs, delivers maximum pear impact at a higher CTW commitment. Buyers who skip this decision and go straight to price comparison almost always end up confused by why two similarly priced bracelets look completely different. The East-West Mandate is not a quirk — it is what makes pear diamond bracelets a distinct visual category worth owning. And the CTW Divide is not a technicality — it is the difference between buying 1.5 carats of pear diamonds and buying 5.25 carats of pear diamonds for what appears to be a similar number.
>
> — Farzana Hasan, Fine Jewelry Analyst

The six pear diamond bracelet designs at Blue Nile cover the full range from $7,105 to $37,925, from 3 CTW to 12½ CTW, and from the most wearable accent format to the most elaborate cluster design. The category is narrower than the ring or earring lineup, but it is well-structured: each piece has a distinct purpose, a distinct format, and a distinct buyer. Once you know which format you want and whether lab or natural is the right call for your situation, the product choice becomes obvious.

## Frequently Asked Questions

### What is a pear diamond bracelet?

A pear diamond bracelet is any bracelet that features pear-cut (teardrop-shaped) diamonds as the primary or accent stone. At Blue Nile, the category includes accent tennis bracelets (pear diamonds alternating with round brilliant stones), all-pear east-west tennis bracelets, station bracelets with mixed fancy shapes including pear cuts, rigid bangle bracelets set with pear lab grown diamonds, and alternating multi-shape cluster designs.

### How are pear diamonds set in bracelets?

Pear diamonds in bracelets are always set east-west — horizontally across the wrist, with the stone's point and belly oriented perpendicular to the direction the bracelet runs. Vertical setting is geometrically impractical at bracelet stone sizes because the pear's length-to-width ratio would make each link too tall and too rigid to flex correctly. East-west orientation creates compact links with correct flex mechanics.

### What does CTW mean on a pear diamond bracelet?

CTW is total carat weight — the combined weight of all diamonds in the piece. In an all-pear tennis bracelet, every carat is a pear stone. In an accent bracelet, the CTW covers both pear and round stones combined; the pear portion is approximately 40–60% of the stated total. In a station bracelet, the CTW covers only the featured station stones, not the connecting chain. Never compare CTW across different bracelet formats.

### What is the best pear diamond tennis bracelet?

The [Dainty East-West Pear Cut Diamond Tennis Bracelet in 14K White Gold (5¼ CTW) at $16,285](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/bracelets/dainty-east-west-pear-cut-diamond-tennis-bracelet-in-14k-white-gold-5-1-4-ct-tw-item-752577?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the definitive all-pear diamond tennis bracelet in the Blue Nile lineup. Every stone is a pear diamond, set east-west in a continuous line for maximum pear diamond presence. No round accents, no format compromise.

### What is a pear diamond accent bracelet?

A pear diamond accent bracelet features pear diamonds prominently but alternates them with round brilliants or other shapes in a repeating sequence. The pear stones are the larger, more prominent elements but share CTW with the accent stones. The [Extraordinary Collection Pear Diamond Accent Tennis (3 CTW) at $7,105](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/bracelets/diamond-tennis-bracelet-with-pear-diamond-accent-in-14k-white-gold-3-ct-tw-item-753000?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the entry-level option.

### What is the difference between a station bracelet and a tennis bracelet?

A tennis bracelet is a continuous line of diamonds — every link is a stone, no interruption. A station bracelet features diamonds at set intervals (the stations) connected by a plain metal chain or wire between them. Station bracelets appear more delicate in overall structure but concentrate their CTW at the featured positions, making each individual station stone larger and heavier than equivalent-CTW tennis stones.

### Are lab grown pear diamonds worth it in bracelets?

Yes, for buyers prioritizing diamond mass per dollar over natural origin. Lab grown pear diamonds are chemically identical to natural stones — same refractive index, same hardness, same optical behavior. At bracelet stone sizes (typically under 0.35ct each), the difference is invisible even to a gemologist without documentation. The [Pear Lab Grown Bangle (8 CTW, $12,145)](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/bracelets/pear-lab-grown-diamond-bangle-bracelet-in-14k-white-gold-8-ct-tw-item-753884?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) delivers more carat weight than any natural pear bracelet in the lineup at a lower price point.

### What size pear diamonds are used in tennis bracelets?

Individual stone sizes in pear diamond tennis bracelets are rarely disclosed in the product listing — only total CTW is prominently stated. Typical individual stone sizes range from 0.08 to 0.35 carats per stone. A 5.25 CTW bracelet with 20 pear diamonds would average 0.26ct per stone. For specific stone count and individual sizes, contact Blue Nile's customer service before purchase if this detail is important to your decision.

### Does the orientation of pear diamonds matter in bracelets?

Yes, and the orientation is determined by the setting — buyers do not choose it. All commercially produced pear diamond bracelets use east-west (horizontal) orientation because vertical orientation is structurally impractical. Within east-west settings, you can observe whether adjacent pear points face the same direction (producing a consistent visual pattern) or alternate in direction (producing a more dynamic rhythm). This detail affects the sparkle pattern but is not user-selectable on standard bracelet designs.

### Can I stack a pear diamond bracelet with other bracelets?

Yes. The east-west pear tennis bracelet stacks best with thinner contrast pieces — plain metal bands, thin chains, or a watch. Allow at least 2mm of space between a tennis bracelet and adjacent stacking pieces to prevent prong contact. The pear lab grown bangle functions as a rigid anchor in a stack and pairs naturally with flexible chains on either side. Avoid stacking two diamond tennis bracelets directly against each other; the prong-to-prong contact causes wear over time.

### What metal is best for a pear diamond bracelet?

14K white gold maximizes contrast with colorless pear diamonds, making stones appear brighter. 14K yellow gold creates a warmer aesthetic and is correct for buyers whose engagement ring and existing fine jewelry are yellow gold. Match the bracelet metal to the metal family of the fine jewelry you wear most consistently. Mixing metal families works in a stack only when at least one other piece deliberately bridges the two tones.

### What is the difference between a pear diamond bangle and a tennis bracelet?

A tennis bracelet is flexible — it is made of individually linked elements and bends with the wrist. A bangle is a rigid circular band that passes over the hand to rest on the wrist. Tennis bracelets can be adjusted in length by adding or removing links; bangles cannot be resized once made. For bangles, fit is determined by the hand's widest point (fingers pressed together), not the wrist circumference.

### How do I clean a pear diamond bracelet?

Soak in warm water with two drops of dish soap for 10–15 minutes. Scrub gently between prongs and links with a soft-bristle brush. Rinse with clean warm water and air dry on a soft cloth. Do not use ultrasonic cleaners on prong-set bracelets without professional inspection first — the vibration can loosen prongs that show any wear. Blue Nile's service plan includes professional cleaning annually, which is the preferred method for high-CTW pieces.

### How often should a pear diamond bracelet be inspected?

For bracelets worn daily, professional prong inspection is recommended every 12–18 months. Pear diamonds have a pointed tip that is more vulnerable to chipping from direct impact than round stones — daily bracelet activity (typing, gym use, carrying bags) is not a risk, but a direct blow to the stone's point against a hard surface can cause a chip in the worst case. Annual inspection catches any prong loosening before stone loss occurs.

